SB 1546
1 (ii) Software incorporated into a video game that is limited to providing interaction only
2 with the features of the video game, if the software does not respond to input on topics such
3 as mental health, self-harm, sexually explicit conduct or other topics unrelated to the fea-
4 tures of the video game; or
5 (iii) A stand-alone consumer electronic device that functions as a speaker and voice
6 command interface or acts as a voice-activated virtual assistant and does not perform
7 actions of the type described in subparagraph (A) of this paragraph.
8 (b) “Artificial intelligence platform” means a website, application or other combination
9 of software and hardware that allows or facilitates operation of and interaction with an ar-
10 tificial intelligence companion.
11 (c) “Operator” means a person that operates or makes an artificial intelligence platform
12 or artificial intelligence companion available to users in this state.
13 (d) “Sexually explicit conduct” has the meaning given that term in ORS 163.665.
14 (2) A provider of an artificial intelligence companion or an operator of an artificial in-
15 telligence platform that provides access to an artificial intelligence companion shall provide
16 on the artificial intelligence platform, and cause the artificial intelligence companion to pre-
17 cede each response with, a clear and conspicuous notice that indicates that a user is inter-
18 acting with artificially generated output and not a natural person.
19 (3)(a) An operator may not allow users in this state access to an artificial intelligence
20 companion or artificial intelligence platform unless the operator has a protocol for using
21 evidence-based methods for detecting input from the user that consists of suicidal ideation
22 or intent or self-harm ideation or intent and that prevents the provision of content to the
23 user that could cause suicidal ideation, suicide or self-harm in the user.
24 (b) The protocol described in paragraph (a) of this subsection at a minimum must:
25 (A) Notify any user that expresses suicidal ideation or intent or self-harm ideation or
26 intent with a referral to a suicide hotline or crisis management agency or similar resources
27 that provide appropriate counseling; and
28 (B) Immediately interrupt a conversation between an artificial intelligence companion
29 and a user if the conversation consists of user suicidal ideation or intent or self harm
30 ideation or intent.
31 (c) An operator shall publish on the operator’s artificial intelligence platform the details
32 of the operator’s protocol.
33 (4)(a) If an operator has reason to believe that a user of the operator’s artificial intelli-
34 gence companion or artificial intelligence platform is a minor, the operator shall:
35 (A) State that the operator’s artificial intelligence companion or artificial intelligence
36 platform may not be suitable for minors;
37 (B) Disclose to the user that the user is interacting with artificially generated output;
38 (C) Provide a clear and conspicuous reminder at a minimum of every hour of interaction
39 that the user should take a break from interactions with the artificial intelligence companion
40 or artificial intelligence platform, along with a further reminder that the user is interacting
41 with artificially generated output; and
42 (D) Use reasonable measures to ensure that the artificial intelligence companion does
43 not produce visual representations of sexually explicit conduct or suggest or state that the
44 minor should engage in sexually explicit conduct.
45 (b) In the circumstances described in paragraph (a) of this subsection, an operator may
[2]

SB 1546
1 not cause an artificial intelligence companion to:
2 (A) Deliver to a user, either on a variable schedule or otherwise, a system of rewards
3 or affirmations with the purpose of reinforcing behavior or maximizing the time during
4 which the user engages with the artificial intelligence companion;
5 (B) Generate in response to a user’s indication of a desire to end a conversation, reduce
6 engagement time or delete the user’s account unsolicited messages of simulated emotional
7 distress, loneliness, or abandonment or otherwise attempt to arouse guilt or sympathy in the
8 user; or
9 (C) Make a material misrepresentation about the artificial intelligence companion’s
10 identity, capabilities, training data or about whether the user is interacting with artificially
11 generated output, including when the user directly questions the artificial intelligence com-
12 panion about any of these topics.
13 (5)(a) Not later than December 31 of each year, an operator shall report to the Oregon
14 Health Authority:
15 (A) The number of times during the calendar year preceding the report in which the op-
16 erator provided a referral under subsection (3) of this section; and
17 (B) The details of the operator’s protocol under subsection (3) of this section.
18 (b) An operator may not report to the authority any personal information that identifies
19 an individual.
20 (c) The authority by rule may specify the form, format and contents of the report re-
21 quired under this subsection.
22 (d) The authority shall publish on the authority’s website a summary of the reports the
23 authority received from operators during the previous calendar year.
24 SECTION 2. (1) An individual who suffers an ascertainable loss of money or property or
25 other injury in fact as a result of an operator’s violation of section 1 of this 2026 Act may
26 bring an action in a court of this state to recover:
27 (a) The greater of the individual’s actual damages or statutory damages of $1,000 for each
28 violation; and
29 (b) An injunction to prevent or restrain the violation.
30 (2) A court may award a prevailing plaintiff attorney fees and costs in an action under
31 this section.
32 (3) Relief or a recovery under this section does not relieve an operator of any duty,
33 remedy or obligation to which the operator is subject under other applicable law.
